## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

Your code is a **timeout enforcement** pattern with a **ThreadAbortException-as-control-flow** catch block:

| API Found | Issue on .NET 8 |
|-----------|-----------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never fires (no abort = no exception) |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(), token);

        try
        {
            // Block until task completes or timeout fires.
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout.
            return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ae) when (ae.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ae.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### Key Differences

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|----------------|--------|
| Dedicated `Thread` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run` (uses thread pool) |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` to wait | `Task.WaitAsync(token)` with auto-cancel |
| `thread.Abort()` forcibly kills thread | `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` signals cooperatively |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed — no forced abort to reset |

### ⚠️ Critical Pitfall: Cooperative ≠ Preemptive

The old code **forcibly killed** the thread mid-execution. The new code **cannot do that**. If `work()` is a tight CPU loop or blocking I/O that never checks cancellation, **it will keep running** in the background after the timeout fires.

**If `work` is code you control**, pass the token through:

```csharp
// Updated signature to accept cancellation
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller example — work checks the token at regular checkpoints
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in largeCollection)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

**If `work` is uncooperative code you cannot modify**, the only true equivalent to `Thread.Abort` is running it in a **separate process** and calling `Process.Kill()` on timeout.

### Other Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource` | Leaks internal timers. Always `using`. |
| Swallowing `OperationCanceledException` | The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` guard ensures you only catch *your* timeout, not an unrelated cancellation. |
| Assuming instant stop | Cancellation is checked at the *next* checkpoint. Long gaps between checks = delayed cancellation. |
| Fire-and-forget background work | After timeout, `Task.Run` may still be running. If `work` holds resources (DB connections, file handles), register cleanup via `token.Register(() => ...)`. |
